# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-performance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] In routers and switches, **active queue management** (**AQM**) is the policy of dropping packets inside a buffer associated with a network interface controller (NIC) before that buffer becomes full, often with the goal of reducing network congestion or improving end-to-end latency.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] This task is performed by the network scheduler, which for this purpose uses various algorithms such as random early detection (RED), Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN), or controlled delay (CoDel).
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] RFC 7567 recommends active queue management as a best practice.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] An Internet router typically maintains a set of queues, one or more per interface, that hold packets scheduled to go out on that interface.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] Historically, such queues use a *drop-tail* discipline: a packet is put onto the queue if the queue is shorter than its maximum size (measured in packets or in bytes), and dropped otherwise.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] Active queue disciplines drop or mark packets before the queue is full.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] Typically, they operate by maintaining one or more drop/mark probabilities, and occasionally dropping or marking packets according to the probabilities before the queue is full.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] Drop-tail queues have a tendency to penalise bursty flows, and to cause global synchronization between flows.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] By dropping packets probabilistically, AQM disciplines typically avoid both of these issues.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] By providing endpoints with congestion indication before the queue is full, AQM disciplines are able to maintain a shorter queue length than drop-tail queues, which combats bufferbloat and reduces network latency.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] Early AQM disciplines (notably RED and SRED) require careful tuning of their parameters in order to provide good performance.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] These systems are not optimally behaved from a control theory perspective.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] Modern AQM disciplines (ARED, Blue, PI, CoDel, CAKE) are self-tuning, and can be run with their default parameters in most circumstances.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] An active queue management and denial-of-Service (AQM&DoS) simulation platform is established based on the NS-2 simulation code of the RRED algorithm.
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] The AQM&DoS simulation platform can simulate a variety of DoS attacks (Distributed DoS, Spoofing DoS, Low-rate DoS, etc.) and AQM algorithms (RED, RRED, SFB, etc.).
[src:network-performance/active-queue-management] It automatically calculates and records the average throughput of normal TCP flows before and after DoS attacks to facilitate the analysis of the impact of DoS attacks on normal TCP flows and AQM algorithms.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Some communications equipment manufacturers designed unnecessarily large buffers into some of their network products.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] In such equipment, bufferbloat occurs when a network link becomes congested, causing packets to become queued for long periods in these oversized buffers.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] In a first-in first-out queuing system, overly large buffers result in longer queues and higher latency, and do not improve network throughput.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] It can also be induced by specific slow-speed connections hindering the on-time delivery of other packets.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The bufferbloat phenomenon was described as early as 1985.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] It gained more widespread attention starting in 2009.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] According to some sources, the most frequent cause of high latency ("lag") in online video games is local home network bufferbloat.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] High latency can render modern online gaming impossible.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] An established rule of thumb for the network equipment manufacturers was to provide buffers large enough to accommodate at least 250 ms of buffering for a stream of traffic passing through a device.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] For example, a router's Gigabit Ethernet interface would require a relatively large 32 MB buffer.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Such sizing of the buffers can lead to failure of the TCP congestion control algorithm.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The buffers then take some time to drain, before congestion control resets and the TCP connection ramps back up to speed and fills the buffers again.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Bufferbloat thus causes problems such as high and variable latency, and choking network bottlenecks for all other flows as the buffer becomes full of the packets of one TCP stream and other packets are then dropped.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] A bloated buffer has an effect only when this buffer is actually used.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] In other words, oversized buffers have a damaging effect only when the link they buffer becomes a bottleneck.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The size of the buffer serving a bottleneck can be measured using the ping utility provided by most operating systems.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] First, the other host should be pinged continuously; then, a several-second-long download from it should be started and stopped a few times.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] By design, the TCP congestion avoidance algorithm will rapidly fill up the bottleneck on the route.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] If downloading (and uploading, respectively) correlates with a direct and important increase in the round-trip time reported by ping, then it demonstrates that the buffer of the current bottleneck in the download (and upload, respectively) direction is bloated.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Since the increase in the round-trip time is caused by the buffer on the bottleneck, the maximum increase gives a rough estimation of its size in milliseconds.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] In the previous example, using an advanced traceroute tool instead of the simple pinging (for example, MTR) will not only demonstrate the existence of a bloated buffer on the bottleneck, but will also pinpoint its location in the network.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Traceroute achieves this by displaying the route (path) and measuring transit delays of packets across the network.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The history of the route is recorded as round-trip times of the packets received from each successive host (remote node) in the route (path).
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Most TCP congestion control algorithms rely on measuring the occurrence of packet drops to determine the available bandwidth between two ends of a connection.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The algorithms speed up the data transfer until packets start to drop, then slow down the transmission rate.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Ideally, they keep adjusting the transmission rate until it reaches an equilibrium speed of the link.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] So that the algorithms can select a suitable transfer speed, the feedback about packet drops must occur in a timely manner.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] With a large buffer that has been filled, the packets will arrive at their destination, but with a higher latency.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The packets were not dropped, so TCP does not slow down once the uplink has been saturated, further filling the buffer.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Newly arriving packets are dropped only when the buffer is fully saturated.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Once this happens, TCP may even decide that the path of the connection has changed, and again go into the more aggressive search for a new operating point.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Packets are queued within a network buffer before being transmitted; in problematic situations, packets are dropped only if the buffer is full.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] On older routers, buffers were fairly small, so they filled quickly, and therefore packets began to drop shortly after the link became saturated, so the TCP protocol could adjust, and the issue would not become apparent.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] On newer routers, buffers have become large enough to hold several seconds of buffered data.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] To TCP, a congested link can appear to be operating normally as the buffer fills.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The TCP algorithm is unaware that the link is congested and does not start to take corrective action until the buffer finally overflows and packets are dropped.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] All packets passing through a simple buffer implemented as a single queue will experience similar delay, so the latency of any connection that passes through a filled buffer will be affected.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Available channel bandwidth can also end up being unused, as some fast destinations may not be promptly reached due to buffers clogged with data awaiting delivery to slow destinations.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] These effects impair the interactivity of applications using other network protocols, including UDP used in latency-sensitive applications like VoIP and online gaming.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Regardless of bandwidth requirements, any type of service that requires consistently low latency or jitter-free transmission can be affected by bufferbloat.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Such services include digital voice calls (VOIP), online gaming, video chat, and other interactive applications such as radio streaming, video on demand, and remote login.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] When the bufferbloat phenomenon is present and the network is under load, even normal web page loads can take many seconds to complete, or simple DNS queries can fail due to timeouts.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Actually any TCP connection can timeout and disconnect, and UDP packets can get discarded.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Since the continuation of a TCP download stream depends on acknowledgement (ACK) packets in the upload stream, a bufferbloat problem in the upload can cause failure of other non-related download applications, because the client ACK packets do not timely reach the internet server.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The DSLReports Speedtest was an easy-to-use test that included a score for bufferbloat.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The DSLReports site went fully offline on March 26, 2025.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The ICSI Netalyzr was another on-line tool that could be used for checking networks for the presence of bufferbloat, together with checking for many other common configuration problems.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The service was shut down in March 2019.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] In the absence of DSLReports and Netalyzr, current browser-based bufferbloat tests include the Waveform Bufferbloat Test and Y2KDASH, which samples loaded latency continuously rather than in a single-shot test.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The bufferbloat.net web site lists tools and procedures for determining whether a connection has excess buffering that will slow it down.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Several technical solutions exist which can be broadly grouped into two categories: solutions that target the network and solutions that target the endpoints.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The two types of solutions are often complementary.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The problem sometimes arrives with a combination of fast and slow network paths.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Network solutions generally take the form of queue management algorithms.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] This type of solution has been the focus of the IETF AQM working group.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] The problem may also be mitigated by reducing the buffer size on the OS and network hardware; however, this is often not configurable, and optimal buffer size is dependent on line rate, which may differ for different destinations.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] Utilizing DiffServ (and employing multiple priority-based queues) helps in prioritizing transmission of low-latency traffic (such as VoIP, videoconferencing, gaming), relegating dealing with congestion and bufferbloat onto non-prioritized traffic.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] For the longest delay TCP connections to still get their fair share of the bandwidth, the buffer size should be at least the bandwidth-delay product divided by the square root of the number of simultaneous streams.
[src:network-performance/bufferbloat] A typical rule of thumb is 50 ms of line rate data, but some popular consumer grade switches only have 1 ms, which may result in extra bandwidth loss on the longer delay connections in case of local contention with others.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Network protocols that use aggressive retransmissions to compensate for packet loss due to congestion can increase congestion, even after the initial load has been reduced to a level that would not normally have induced network congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Such networks exhibit two stable states under the same level of load.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The stable state with low throughput is known as **congestive collapse**.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Networks use **congestion control** and **congestion avoidance** techniques to try to avoid collapse.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] These include: window reduction in TCP, and fair queueing in devices such as routers and network switches.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Other techniques that address congestion include priority schemes, which transmit some packets with higher priority ahead of others and the explicit allocation of network resources to specific flows through the use of admission control.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Network resources are limited, including router processing time and link throughput.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Resource contention may occur on networks in several common circumstances.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] A wireless LAN is easily filled by a single personal computer.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Even on fast computer networks, the backbone can easily be congested by a few servers and client PCs.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Denial-of-service attacks by botnets are capable of filling even the largest Internet backbone network links, generating large-scale network congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] In telephone networks, a mass call event can overwhelm digital telephone circuits, in what can otherwise be defined as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Congestive collapse (or congestion collapse) is the condition in which congestion prevents or limits useful communication.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Congestion collapse generally occurs at choke points in the network, where incoming traffic exceeds outgoing bandwidth.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Connection points between a local area network and a wide area network are common choke points.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] When a network is in this condition, it settles into a stable state where traffic demand is high but little useful throughput is available, during which packet delay and loss occur and quality of service is extremely poor.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Congestive collapse was identified as a possible problem by 1984.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] It was first observed on the early Internet in October 1986, when the NSFNET phase-I backbone dropped three orders of magnitude from its capacity of 32 kbit/s to 40 bit/s, which continued until end nodes started implementing Van Jacobson and Sally Floyd's congestion control between 1987 and 1988.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] When more packets were sent than could be handled by intermediate routers, the intermediate routers discarded many packets, expecting the endpoints of the network to retransmit the information.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] However, early TCP implementations had poor retransmission behavior.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] When this packet loss occurred, the endpoints sent extra packets that repeated the information lost, doubling the incoming rate.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Congestion control modulates traffic entry into a telecommunications network in order to avoid congestive collapse resulting from oversubscription.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This is typically accomplished by reducing the rate of packets.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Whereas congestion control prevents senders from overwhelming the *network*, flow control prevents the sender from overwhelming the *receiver*.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The theory of congestion control was pioneered by Frank Kelly, who applied microeconomic theory and convex optimization theory to describe how individuals controlling their own rates can interact to achieve an *optimal* network-wide rate allocation.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Examples of *optimal* rate allocation are max-min fair allocation and Kelly's suggestion of proportionally fair allocation, although many others are possible.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Let $x_{i}$ be the rate of flow i , $c_{l}$ be the capacity of link l , and $r_{li}$ be 1 if flow i uses link l and 0 otherwise.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Let x , c and R be the corresponding vectors and matrix.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Let $U(x)$ be an increasing, strictly concave function, called the utility, which measures how much benefit a user obtains by transmitting at rate x .
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The Lagrange dual of this problem decouples so that each flow sets its own rate, based only on a *price* signaled by the network.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Each link capacity imposes a constraint, which gives rise to a Lagrange multiplier, $p_{l}$ .
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The sum of these multipliers, $y_{i}=\sum _{l}p_{l}r_{li},$ is the price to which the flow responds.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Congestion control then becomes a distributed optimization algorithm.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Many current congestion control algorithms can be modeled in this framework, with $p_{l}$ being either the loss probability or the queueing delay at link l .
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] A major weakness is that it assigns the same price to all flows, while sliding window flow control causes burstiness that causes different flows to observe different loss or delay at a given link.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The correct endpoint behavior is usually to repeat dropped information, but progressively slow the repetition rate.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Provided all endpoints do this, the congestion lifts and the network resumes normal behavior.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Other strategies such as slow start ensure that new connections do not overwhelm the router before congestion detection initiates.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Common router congestion avoidance mechanisms include fair queuing and other scheduling algorithms, and random early detection where packets are randomly dropped as congestion is detected.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This proactively triggers the endpoints to slow transmission before congestion collapse occurs.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Some end-to-end protocols are designed to behave well under congested conditions; TCP is a well-known example.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The first TCP implementations to handle congestion were described in 1984, but Van Jacobson's inclusion of an open source solution in the Berkeley Standard Distribution UNIX ("BSD") in 1988 first provided good behavior.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Protocols built atop UDP must handle congestion independently.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Protocols that transmit at a fixed rate, independent of congestion, can be problematic.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Real-time streaming protocols, including many Voice over IP protocols, have this property.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Thus, special measures, such as quality of service, must be taken to keep packets from being dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Connection-oriented protocols, such as the widely used TCP protocol, watch for packet loss or queuing delay to adjust their transmission rate.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Various network congestion avoidance processes support different trade-offs.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The TCP congestion avoidance algorithm is the primary basis for congestion control on the Internet.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Problems occur when concurrent TCP flows experience tail-drops, especially when bufferbloat is present.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This delayed packet loss interferes with TCP's automatic congestion avoidance.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] All flows that experience this packet loss begin a TCP retrain at the same moment – this is called TCP global synchronization.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Active queue management (AQM) is the reordering or dropping of network packets inside a transmit buffer that is associated with a network interface controller (NIC).
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This task is performed by the network scheduler.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] One solution is to use random early detection (RED) on the network equipment's egress queue.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] On networking hardware ports with more than one egress queue, weighted random early detection (WRED) can be used.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] RED indirectly signals TCP sender and receiver by dropping some packets, e.g. when the average queue length is more than a threshold (e.g.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] 50%) and deletes linearly or cubically more packets, up to e.g.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The robust random early detection (RRED) algorithm was proposed to improve the TCP throughput against denial-of-service (DoS) attacks, particularly low-rate denial-of-service (LDoS) attacks.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Experiments confirmed that RED-like algorithms were vulnerable under LDoS attacks due to the oscillating TCP queue size caused by the attacks.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Some network equipment is equipped with ports that can follow and measure each flow and are thereby able to signal a too big bandwidth flow according to some quality of service policy.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] A policy could then divide the bandwidth among all flows by some criteria.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Another approach is to use Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN).
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] ECN is used only when two hosts signal that they want to use it.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] With this method, a protocol bit is used to signal explicit congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This is better than the indirect congestion notification signaled by packet loss by the RED/WRED algorithms, but it requires support by both hosts.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] When a router receives a packet marked as ECN-capable and the router anticipates congestion, it sets the ECN flag, notifying the sender of congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The sender should respond by decreasing its transmission bandwidth, e.g., by decreasing its sending rate by reducing the TCP window size or by other means.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The L4S protocol is an enhanced version of ECN that allows senders to collaborate with network devices to control congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Congestion avoidance can be achieved efficiently by reducing traffic.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] When an application requests a large file, graphic or web page, it usually advertises a *window* of between 32K and 64K.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This results in the server sending a full window of data (assuming the file is larger than the window).
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] When many applications simultaneously request downloads, this data can create a congestion point at an upstream provider.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] By reducing the window advertisement, the remote servers send less data, thus reducing the congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Backward ECN (BECN) is another proposed congestion notification mechanism.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] It uses ICMP source quench messages as an IP signaling mechanism to implement a basic ECN mechanism for IP networks, keeping congestion notifications at the IP level and requiring no negotiation between network endpoints.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Effective congestion notifications can be propagated to transport layer protocols, such as TCP and UDP, for the appropriate adjustments.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The protocols that avoid congestive collapse generally assume that data loss is caused by congestion.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] On wired networks, errors during transmission are rare.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] WiFi, 3G and other networks with a radio layer are susceptible to data loss due to interference and may experience poor throughput in some cases.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The TCP connections running over a radio-based physical layer see the data loss and tend to erroneously believe that congestion is occurring.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] The slow-start protocol performs badly for short connections.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Older web browsers created many short-lived connections and opened and closed the connection for each file.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] This kept most connections in the slow start mode.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Initial performance can be poor, and many connections never get out of the slow-start regime, significantly increasing latency.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] To avoid this problem, modern browsers either open multiple connections simultaneously or reuse one connection for all files requested from a particular server.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Admission control is any system that requires devices to receive permission before establishing new network connections.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] If the new connection risks creating congestion, permission can be denied.
[src:network-performance/network-congestion-avoidance] Examples include Contention-Free Transmission Opportunities (CFTXOPs) in the ITU-T G.hn standard for home networking over legacy wiring, Resource Reservation Protocol for IP networks and Stream Reservation Protocol for Ethernet.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:network-performance/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:network-performance/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] In the conventional tail drop algorithm, a router or other network component buffers as many packets as it can, and simply drops the ones it cannot buffer.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] If buffers are constantly full, the network is congested.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Tail drop distributes buffer space unfairly among traffic flows.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Tail drop can also lead to TCP global synchronization as all TCP connections "hold back" simultaneously, and then step forward simultaneously.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Networks become under-utilized and flooded—alternately, in waves.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] RED addresses these issues by pre-emptively dropping packets before the buffer becomes completely full.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] It uses predictive models to decide which packets to drop.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] It was invented in the early 1990s by Sally Floyd and Van Jacobson.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] RED monitors the average queue size and drops (or marks when used in conjunction with ECN) packets based on statistical probabilities.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] If the buffer is almost empty, then all incoming packets are accepted.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] As the queue grows, the probability for dropping an incoming packet grows too.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] When the buffer is full, the probability has reached 1 and all incoming packets are dropped.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] RED is more fair than tail drop, in the sense that it does not possess a bias against bursty traffic that uses only a small portion of the bandwidth.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] The more a host transmits, the more likely it is that its packets are dropped as the probability of a host's packet being dropped is proportional to the amount of data it has in a queue.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Early detection helps avoid TCP global synchronization.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] According to Van Jacobson, "there are not one, but two bugs in classic RED." Improvements to the algorithm were developed, and a draft paper was prepared, but the paper was never published, and the improvements were not widely disseminated or implemented.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] There has been some work in trying to finish off the research and fix the bugs.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Pure RED does not accommodate quality of service (QoS) differentiation.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Weighted RED (WRED) and RED with In and Out (RIO) provide early detection with QoS considerations.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] In weighted RED you can have different probabilities for different priorities (IP precedence, DSCP) and/or queues.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] The adaptive RED or active RED (ARED) algorithm infers whether to make RED more or less aggressive based on the observation of the average queue length.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] If the average queue length oscillates around *min* threshold then early detection is too aggressive.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] On the other hand, if the average queue length oscillates around *max* threshold then early detection is being too conservative.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] The algorithm changes the probability according to how aggressively it senses it has been discarding traffic.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] See Srikant for an in-depth account on these techniques and their analysis.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Robust random early detection (RRED) algorithm was proposed to improve the TCP throughput against Denial-of-Service (DoS) attacks, particularly Low-rate Denial-of-Service (LDoS) attacks.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] Experiments have confirmed that the existing RED-like algorithms are notably vulnerable under Low-rate Denial-of-Service (LDoS) attacks due to the oscillating TCP queue size caused by the attacks.
[src:network-performance/random-early-detection] RRED algorithm can significantly improve the performance of TCP under Low-rate Denial-of-Service attacks.
